               <head>Polyglot Bible</head>
                    
               
               
               
               <msContents class="lccn.loc.gov/sh85077732  lccn.loc.gov/sh2014001944" rend="visible">
                        
                  
                  
                  
                  <summary>Polyglot Bible and fragments of liturgical texts. </summary>
                        
                  
                  
                  
                  <textLang mainLang="he" otherLangs="la gre he syc-Syrc tmr-Hebr ara per gez-Ethi cop-Copt spa ita fr ger"/>
                        
                  
                  
                  
                  <msItem rend="">
                            
                     
                     
                     
                     <locus from="1r" to="20v"/>
                            
                     
                     
                     
                     <title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Polyglot</title>
                            
                     
                     
                     
                     <title xml:lang="he">פוליגלוט</title>
                            
                     
                     
                     
                     <note>
                        
                        
                        
                        <p>The title-page constists of an ornamental design with the title
                                    in the centre. </p>
                        
                        
                        
                        <p>The manuscript contains biblical and
                                    liturgical pieces, respectively written in the following
                                    languages: Latin, Greek, Hebrew, Syriac, Aramaic, Ethiopic,
                                    Arabic, Persian, Coptic, Spanish, Italian, French and German, in
                                    the following order: 1. Formula Orandi, 2. Fidei Confessio, 3.
                                    The Ten Commandments, 4. Canticum B. Virginis, 5. Canticum
                                    Zachariae, 6. Canticum Simeonis, 7. Institutio Baptismatis, 8.
                                    Institutio Eucharistiae. </p>
                        
                        
                        
                        <p>The Latin, Greek, Syriac,
                                    Arabic, Ethiopic, and Persian of the biblical passages are taken
                                    from the Walton's SS. Biblia Polyglotta (London, 1657). Under
                                    the Coptic version of the Lord's Prayer is written: "Ex
                                    Celeberrimi Viri Athanasii Kircheri Prodromo Copto."</p>
                     
                     
                     
                     </note>
                            
                     
                     
                     
                     <decoNote type="illustration">18 ful-page illustrations of biblical
                                text, in brown ink and colors. <locus n="1v, 2v, 3v, 4v, 5v, 6v, 7v, 9v, 10v, 11v, 12v, 13v, 14v, 15v, 16v, 17v, 18v"/>
                     
                     
                     
                     </decoNote>
                            
                     
                     
                     
                     <decoNote type="other">1 unfinished coat of arms, ink and pencil. <locus n="20r"/>
                     
                     
                     
                     </decoNote>
                            
                     
                     
                     
                     <decoNote type="other">
                        
                        
                        
                        <locus n="1r"/>Decorated title-page within an
                                arch, in black and brown ink. </decoNote>
                        
                  
                  
                  
                  </msItem>
                    
               
               
               
